soc.message

Class SOCMessageTemplateMs

  • java.lang.Object
    • soc.message.SOCMessage
      • soc.message.SOCMessageTemplateMs
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, SOCMessageMulti
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    SOCGameOptionInfo, SOCGamesWithOptions, SOCLocalizedStrings, SOCScenarioInfo

    public abstract class SOCMessageTemplateMs
extends SOCMessage
implements SOCMessageMulti
    Template for message types with variable number of string parameters. You will have to write parseDataStr, because of its subclass return type and because it's static. Each parameter (separated by SEP) is passed to parseDataStr as a string in the list.

    Sample implementation: 

    
   // Format of s: GAMESWITHOPTIONS { SEP gameName SEP gameOptStr }*
   // A game with empty options has "-" as its gameOptStr.
   public static SOCGamesWithOptions parseDataStr(List s)
   {
       if (s == null)
           s = new ArrayList();
       else if ((s.size() % 2) != 0)
           return null;  // must have an even # of strings

       // parseData_FindEmptyStrs(s);  // EMPTYSTR -> "" -- not needed for this type

       return new SOCGamesWithOptions(s);
   }

    For notes on the section you must add to SOCMessage.toMsg(String), see SOCMessageMulti.

    Before v2.0.00 this template class also implemented SOCMessageForGame for use by future subclasses, but none of its actual subclasses were game-specific.

    Since:
    1.1.00
    Author:
    Jeremy D Monin <jeremy@nand.net>

    • Field Detail

      • pa

        protected java.util.List<java.lang.String> pa
        List of string parameters, or null if none. Blank field values must be sent over network as SOCMessage.EMPTYSTR because empty pa elements can't be parsed. This List itself should contain "" instead of an EMPTYSTR token; toCmd() will translate "" and null to EMPTYSTR.

        Before v2.0.00, this was an array of Strings.

        Create a new multi-message with string parameters.
        Parameters:
